# What is Version Control and Why Does it Matter

How would you control the versions of an extensive and collaborative project without Version Control Systems? *It would be difficult, wouldn't you agree?!*

------------------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ”¥ **ğŸ‘©â€ğŸ”¬ Hey, I'm building a wonderful project...**

ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ”¬ **Oops, I think you made a mistake in this version.**

**ğŸ‘©â€ğŸ”¬: Oh my God! What do I do now?! I'VE LOST CONTROL!**


------------------------------------------------------------------

Yes, you easily lose control of the project if you don't use control systems.

With version control throughout the project, you will be safer because it will be easy to record the previous states of the code.

Therefore, I really suggest that you use Version Control Systems.

â†’ I also invite you to use the Distributed Version System - [to learn more you can read page one of the Git Book here.](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-About-Version-Control)

Distributed Version Systems allow you to:


------------------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ“ **Well, as the name suggests, the code is distributed on different computers collaborating with different people who will have all the previous versions of the project.**

